body:
@fredbi That's what I was referring to ... I don't think it's possible to do that with the current  template system. Consider the main bit affected:

```
{{ pascalize .Name}} {{ template "schemaType" . }} `
  {{- $prop := . }}
  {{- range $i, $structTag := $.StructTags }}
    {{- if gt $i 0 }} {{ end }}
    {{- template "structTag" dict "Tag" $structTag "Schema" $prop }}
  {{- else }}
    {{- template "structTag" dict "Tag" "json" "Schema" $prop }}
  {{- end }}
  {{- if .XMLName }} xml:"{{ .XMLName }}"{{ end }}
  {{- if .CustomTag }} {{ .CustomTag }}{{ end }}`
{{ end }}
```
(from: `generator/templates/structfield.gotmpl`)


The backticks themselves are literals in the template and there are numerous fields to check for the existence of backticks in the values. If any of those values contain backticks, a different template  would have to be chosen. Compare that with escaping double quotes in all values and using double quotes instead of backticks for the surrounding quotes.

I agree that would be super ugly, but the ugliness is constrained the generated code that is rarely touched. I can try to put together a quick PoC to check whether this is as simple a fix as I presume ... I don't understand the code base well enough to contemplate how this could be done any other way without a complete rewrite of this mechanism. If you have any pointers, I'd be open to try though.

On a related note, I'm reluctant to start work on a fix because I can't get the unit tests in `generator` to pass. Is this a bug I should report or is there something I need to do beyond just calling `go test`?

I'm running tests using: `$ go test ./generator` the output is fairly large, because apparently the tests are logging to stderr, I'm attaching a copy of the output. 

[generator_test_results.txt](https://github.com/go-swagger/go-swagger/files/5553596/generator_test_results.txt)

Idea #1. The whole section starting with backtick:
```
{{ pascalize .Name}} {{ template "schemaType" . }} `
  {{- $prop := . }}
  {{- range $i, $structTag := $.StructTags }}
    {{- if gt $i 0 }} {{ end }}
    {{- template "structTag" dict "Tag" $structTag "Schema" $prop }}
  {{- else }}
    {{- template "structTag" dict "Tag" "json" "Schema" $prop }}
  {{- end }}
  {{- if .XMLName }} xml:"{{ .XMLName }}"{{ end }}
  {{- if .CustomTag }} {{ .CustomTag }}{{ end }}`
{{ end }}
```
could be replaced by a template method on object GenSchema to do the job of expanding all tags, e.g:
```
{{ pascalize .Name}} {{ template "schemaType" . }} {{ .PrintTags }}
{{ end }}
```
This would correspond in `structs.go` to something like:
```go
func (g GenSchema) PrintTag() string {
 ....
}
```
